reviewText: I have mostly good things to say about this DVD compilation, it gives us the best of Miss Jackson during her years on Virgin Records. I have heard alot of complaints about this DVD for the simple fact that it didn't contain the videos for "Twenty Foreplay (which is still unavailable on DVD)courtesy of A&M Records" & "Doesn't Really Matter courtesy of Def Jam Recordings", my guess is Virgin didn't want to pay for the clearance of these videos. As for the DVD itself I have never seen images so clear and heard sound so good, especially when on the 5.1 mode (you hear Janet & her music like you've never heard it before)great job on the new mix!!. It's always nice to see classics like ..."If. , Again, Got til it's Gone and Son of a Gun" just to name a few. My only complaint about the DVD is the fact that the original version of "Someone to call my Lover" was booted for the remix with J.D (coincidence mmmmm I  think not), The 2004 Megamix" was excluded & the photo gallery was a disappointment. I guess I can't complain too much considering the bonus performances. Janet is still in Control!!

reviewText: "From Janet to Damita Jo": The Videos are all of Janet Jackson's videos from 1993-2004.  When comparing these videos to the videos from the "Control" and "Rhythm Nation" videos, these videos are not nearly as innovative or creative, however, the dancing is still groundbreaking, brilliant, and top notch.  Aesthetically, Janet is still beautiful and her physique is unbelievably sculpted.  Do the videos and songs match well?  Sometimes.  But then there are times when Janet's creative side overlaps her logic, and the finished product is not always a beautiful thing.  The videos from 1993-94 were clearly the best on this compilation, especially since she was at her peak at that juncture."That's the Way Love Goes" is starts this DVD off.  This song is Janet's most successful to date.  The video has a relaxing and laid back feel.  Janet is sitting around and dancing with her friends (most of them were her dancers at that time.)  For an added treat, Jennifer Lopez is featured in the video, looking young and vibrant.  Janet's most respected choreography is in the "If" video.  The robotic moves are still popular among Janet fans and non-fans alike.  This video has a Chinese theme to it and features non-stop dancing!  Janet looks especially stunning in this one.  Janet's most sexually racy video to date is arguably "Anytime, Anyplace."  There is nothing special about the video as far as graphics, nor does it include anything over-the-top, but she simply shows her sexual side in such a provocative manner.  The way in which she sashays around the room, the intensity in her eyes, the way she bites into her man's earrings and shares a strawberry with him is unforgettable!  This video is definitely a highlight.  My personal favorite Janet video is "Because of Love."  Janet looks genuinely happy here.  Again, she is featured with her closest friends and it also has some memorable tour footage.  "Again" is another simple video, but the simplicity says so much.  The song is about a woman being hesitant to fall in love with her ex again because he hurt her the first time, but, as the song progresses, she is falling for him.  There is much passion between Janet and actor Gary Dourdan here.  This is another one of my favorites.  "Got `Til It's Gone", "All Nite (Don't Stop)", and "Together Again" are all sup par videos overall.  "Together Again" and "All Nite (Don't Stop)" feature some amazing dancing, but the videos as a whole aren't among Janet's best.  "Together Again" is a song Janet dedicated to friends she has lost to AIDS.  In the video, we find Janet and her dancers outside dancing among elephants and desserts.  Hmmmm, I don't know about you, but I didn't like that very much.  "Everytime" is a beautiful song and has an equally pleasing video.  Janet is swimming around nude with blue contacts and a very delicate look on her face.  I loved the concept.This DVD features a few nice interviews and performances.  If you are vacillating on whether or not you should purchase this DVD, go ahead and pick it up.  I rate it 4 stars because I love it!Mikeisha's Top 51. "Because of Love"2. "Again"3. "Anytime, Anyplace"4. "Everytime"5. "You"

reviewText: One must admit that Jackson does not possess a strong voice; she is able to carry a tune and with her looks, that's about all that is necessary.This collection of videos, although touting all of the four titles of her last four albums, is rather limited in its offerings from the latest, "Damita Jo."  That may be due to the fact that her most recent effort didn't spawn the sales success of the previous offerings.While a good segment of the videos presented here can be found on other compilations, they are still visual "treats" for the artist's many fans.  They show her many different moods and physical changes over the past decade.  Extras, like the "live" performance and the interview segment, serve their purposes, neither adding or detracting from the total package.It would've been a better choice to include the Blackstreet version of "I Get Lonely", though, because it is a far superior rendition than the solo Jackson effort.

reviewText: By the 90's, Janet Jackson decided to do away with the all black military outfits of the Rhythm Nation era and show some skin. Love Will Never Do Without You featured the diva in nothing more than a black top and a pair of jeans that showed off her amazing figure. By the 1993 release of her janet. record, Miss Jackson ventured further into her sexy side in both her music and her videos.That's the Way Love Goes finds Janet and some friends relaxing and swaying to the music in a loft. Keep an eye out for a then unknown J. Lo. Miss Jackson and her dancers show off some spicy moves in a voyeuristic Asian club and the sweet ballad Again reminiscing about a past lover (played by actor Gary Dourdan). The steamy Any Time, Any Place takes the commandment "love thy neighbor as thyself" very literally. It's intensely erotic without being sleazy. J and her girlfriends tease some guys while crossing through the desert in You Want This. Because of Love is kind of boring with close-ups of Janet happily singing to the song and shots from her tour.Got 'til It's Gone is one of the most creative videos I've ever seen. Mixing African and African American cultures of the 60's and 70's, Janet plays a lounge singer crooning to a crowd of cheerful and free people. I'm probably in the minority, but I really dig her hair. Together Again shows humans and animals living side by side harmoniously in a lush utopia and a cool shot of Janet hugging and almost comforting herself. The video for the Deeper Remix is softer and more reflective of loved ones lost to AIDS. The futuristic I Get Lonely is my favorite of the Velvet Rope videos. Shots include Janet riding in back of a car with rain dripping down the window, walking down a long hallway, caressing a male mannequin (sounds weird, but it plays into the song's message), and performing a routine with her dancers while donning men's suits. Go Deep is the house party daydream of a male fan, You mirrors her high energy Velvet Rope performance, and she's partially nude while swimming in the beautiful video for Every Time.All For You is a straight up dance video with Miss Janet spotting a guy on a subway. I hate the remix for Someone To Call My Lover, but the video's cute with Janet driving down a country road and hanging out at a juke joint. I also prefer the original version of Son of a Gun, but seeing Janet play voodoo tricks on a no good man make me laugh everytime I see it.If the whole Super Bowl scandal hadn't happened I think the song and video for I Want You would've done better. It's simple with Janet just cruising through the neighborhood on her way to see her man at night. All Nite (Don't Stop) is another sexy clip shot in an abandoned hotel. I could do without the live performance of Just A Little While. It's not that good, but the extras are nice with an interview with Ryan Seacrest and a behind the scenes look at the making of the Damita Jo album.The dvd isn't perfect (where are Runaway, Twenty Foreplay, and Doesn't Really Matter?), but it's still worth the purchase. Pick it up, I say.
